<div class="page-card" id="document-page">
    <h1 id="title">HexyComb Documentation</h1>

    <h2>Project Overview</h2>
    <p>HexyComb is a simple two player strategy game built using Unity WebGL, React, Express, MongoDB, and WebSockets.</p>

    <h2>Questions</h2>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What is the intended purpose of your application?</h4>
        <p>After an entire semester of working on my HexyComb application, I'm excited to show off the gameplay and functionality. The purpose of the application is to allow players the ability to create accounts, play locally or online (should they pay $0.00 for premium status), invite friends to matches and to track their own gameplay. The game also helps new players learn about the game and even practice by playing puzzles. Though I wanted to include the option to save completed games as structured move lists for future review, I ran out of time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>How are you using React?</h4>
        <p>I have used React mostly for modals in the /play and /profile endpoints, so that users can navigate the page with greater ease and be informed of when they must be premium members to play online. In the future, I plan on using react to visualize past games and maybe for chat logs, so that players can communicate with other during gameplay. </p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What data are you storing in MongoDB?</h4>
        <p>I mostly have account information stored in MongoDB. I really wanted to have a list of moves for each match that was stored, but unfortunately, errors kept appearing and I needed to show what I have functioning. Eventually, I plan on having not only past matches stored in MongoDB, but also invites sent to other users. In its current state, MongoDB is used mainly for account management, but has support for saved games and invite tracking.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What is your profit model?</h4>
        <p>The profit model I designed is based off of the idea that the cost of handling a server would be paid for by the players that use it to connect and play with other players. Premium players unlock online play, the ability to send and accept match invites and the ability to save completed games for later. This profit model is intentionally lightweight, but I plan to add more to this profit model to get invite matches working and saved games to function appropriately.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What went right in the development of this project?</h4>
        <p>A suprising amount of stuff began clicking together when my core systems began finally communicating with one another. Getting Unity WebGL to run inside the express environment was a huge milestone in it of itself, but once I was able to get two players to enter a game with one another, the rest of the features to be implemented became much more managable. Handshakes, though confusing at first, became second hand knowledge and eventually grew into a fully functional cross-technology that feels cohesive.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What went wrong in the development of this project?</h4>
        <p>Most of the issues I encountered happened when errors slipped silently. When no errors appeared in the terminal nor in the console. Unity WebGL is powerful, but it is also extremely particular about how it's served, compressed and initialized. I spent a lot of time researching about Brotli files, MIME types and the Unity Loader before anything was able to be rendered. Multiplayer functionality was it's own can of worms, constantly requiring testing and redesigns. Due to issues with father time, I had to cut the idea of expansion pieces. Debugging and Debug logs took up at least 40% of my time working on this project, but it was for good measure. Nothing really went wrong, but many different issues occured that had to be stamped out, which took away time that could have been used for implementing other features.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What did you learn while developing this project?</h4>
        <p>I learned how to bridge technologies that live in seperate worlds. I learned how Unity communicates with JavaScript through .jslib files, how WebSockets behave inside a Unity WebGl build, how to serialize a game state and how to structure a backend that supports real-time communication and REST endpoints. I learned a lot about how Unity WebGL builds are handled on a browser and, just in general, how to scope project realisitically. I hit a lot of roadblocks and honestly, I wouldn't make it to the end would I have attempted to complete all of the other objectives I really wanted to reach.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>If you were to continue, what would you do to improve your application?</h4>
        <p>I actually do plan on continuing and I have a couple thoughts about where to proceed next. Firstly, I want to flesh out all of the Local and Online Play options, flesh out the Rules and all Account based specifics. I would also like to make it so that a ranking system can be implemented, so that rather than having people connect randomly, they can be paired up with other players at least somewhat equal to their level of play. Another idea I've had is to buy an arduino or raspberry pi and make it so that my server will run on it, instead of having to rely on Redis or MongoDB to store information. This also means that I can have it running in person and the cost of running this would be only the cost of electricity.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>If you went above any beyond, how did you do so?</h4>
        <p>Going above and beyond is a term I find counterintuitive. In a way, I find it similar to "Do your own thing but make it nice". I feel like students who care and make an effort on their own terms are "above and beyond". I implemented a turn based game that can run on the web, multiple condition checks that bridge between the Unity build and the webpage itself, websockets that communicate frequently to ensure that timeouts don't occur, the ability to change usernames and nicknames (not just passwords) and a favicon to make the page look nice. I could go on and on about all the things I changed that make this game stand out, but really, I want to make the point that this question is, in it of itself, meaningless. Having a requirement of "above and beyond", defeats the purpose of going "above and beyond" in the first place. Expecations are subjective after all.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>If you borrowed code or code fragments, where did you get them from?</h4>
        <p>I think I legitmately spent over a 24 hours reading Unity Documentation. Though it provides a lot of really good information about Unity, it's incredibly hard to sit through. Things like <code>.jslib</code> files for premium verification in my Unity WebGL builds and learning how to call Javascript function from Unity was incredibly difficult. I also referenced multiple community exmaples to understand how to bridge Unity WebGL with browser WebSockets, including how to forward messages into Unity using <code>SendMessage</code> and how to expose a JavaScript <code>Send</code> function back to C#. These examples informed the structure of my WebSocket bridge, but all of my gameplay logic, message formats and multiplayer synchronication code were written by me.</p>
    </div>
    
